segments.text: Dr. Gronemann, who has been or was in the College of Education before its inception, right?
Today is November the 3rd.

I am visiting in Dr. Gronemann's home, and we're going to, he's going to share a few of his perceptions and thoughts about happenings at Texas A&M before the College of Education became a College of Education.
And Dr. Gronemann, can you give me a little background
on what the connection was with the College of Engineering and this Department of Education as such.
What was there?
What kind of collaboration was there?
Well, our Department of Industrial Education was within the School of Engineering.
And obviously, our being a department of teacher education,
We had a very close relationship with other departments who were preparing teachers.
Primarily the department of what was known then as Education and Psychology.
Prior to it becoming a part of the College of Education.
And who was in the department, who was head of that educational department?
Department of Education and Psychology at the time that you were working with them?
Professor Wilcox is the first one we worked with.
Succeeding him, we worked then with Dr. Hensarly.
And how long did this continue until, until what time was this, was this in that, in that context where it was part of the College of Engineering?
I came here in 1940.
The Industrial Education Department was within the College of Engineering because there was no College of Education.
We collaborated very closely with the Department of Education and Psychology, primarily with Professor Wilcox, preceding him
I guess we served two deans because of this relationship.
Correct.
However, I guess we were technically a part of the College of Engineering, at least that's
Where did your funding come from?
That's where our funding came from.
But did you get any information on when the Council on Teacher Education was formed or not?
I'm sure it's in the documents.
I don't have that verified yet document.
With the establishment of the Council
I guess it was called Council of Teacher Education, which embodied departments from various colleges.
We reported on educational matters to the dean of education while at the same time keeping our own dean apprised.
Actually, Dean Hubert was Dean of Liberal Arts at first.
It was called Arts and Sciences?
I guess so.
And then it became Liberal Arts.
Yeah.
So he was the dean that you worked under when you were in that department.
We reported to him on matters that pertained to teacher education.
Technically, my boss was Dean Benson.
Oh, okay, very good.
Now, the mission of a college, a land-grant university, is of course teaching, research, and service.
When you were in this department, in the Department of Industrial Education, was there a balance between those three?
What kind of attention was given to the teaching, research, and service?
Did one take priority over another, or were they...
stressed equally?
Well, I presume the major college or school was education.
However, those of us in the separate departments treated the matter as a school-wide exercise.
And we just merely had to keep our deans apprised of what we were doing.
When did this Department of Industrial Education come into the College of Education fold?
Was it when the college was initiated or after?
Was it one of the departments from the very beginning when the college was established?
You mean the College of Education?
Yes, sir.
Industrial education was not a part of the College of Education when the College of Education was established.
We were treated, though, as it were.
We took our responsibilities of departmental operation from the deans of our respective colleges.
or schools as they were known then.
So was there a lot of collaboration then in those days between departments like that?
That had to do with teacher education?
Right.
Yes, and that included ag education.
I was going to say that was the other branch of it.
I don't recall the year that the Council on Teacher Education was established.
But

When it was established, the heads of the departments of education and psychology, ag education, and industrial education worked as though the council was a school or a college, even though they were still separate.
Were you head of that department of industrial education?
Yes.
I was also coordinator of the council on teacher education.
What degrees were offered in that department in industrial ed?
A bachelor of science, a master of science, and a master of education.
And did you have anything to do with establishing the doctoral program?
That's what I heard.
Can you tell me a little bit about that?
How that came about?
idea, how the idea started and what the process was to get it established?
I don't know if I can.
I recall there was a necessity for a college in the state of Texas to offer a doctorate program for teachers of industrial education.
They preferred the teachers in the state
requested that we try to set up such a program rather than make everyone who wanted to have a doctorate degree go through the process of doing it all in areas of general education.
Those in agricultural education and in industrial education felt, we'd like to offer a doctorate in our field, not in general education.
And that's how we came about.
And that doctorate was offered in the department, still through the College of Engineering?
That's right.
And what kinds of classes were taught?
What did you teach when you were in that department?
What were some of the courses that you taught?
Well, you mean generally that I taught or that we had?
Well, both.
Well, in industrial education, our primary purpose was the preparation of teachers for industrial and vocational education.
Vocational education meaning trade and industrial education.
Industrial arts being the group of people
who were not eligible to become teachers under the vocational program due to lack of industrial experience.
So all of the courses were basically geared to the industrial arts and vocational?
Industrial and the vocational.
Industrial arts, do you think, industrial arts
is for those kids in school who are not particularly interested in becoming tradespeople.

Whereas the trade and industrial program was geared to preparing teachers who could, in turn, because of their experience in industry, prepare high school youngsters for direct entry into many trades.
How many years were you in that department?
Well, I came in 1940.
And retired?
I retired in 1967.
And then went to Fresno, California State University for another eight years, because they had no upper limit on age.
So we lived in California pretty long.
Well, we live in Carmel.
You know where that is?
Yes, of course.
That's where I want to live someday.
And I commuted over to Fresno, 150 miles, on Monday, Monday morning, and came back.
They gave me a good schedule over there.
I'd go there Monday morning and came back Thursday afternoon.
Well, you lived in heaven if you were in Carmel because that's one of the most beautiful places.
But the difference is Californians are a different breed of people.
The Texans.
And we were used to Texans.
So you came back?
Yeah.
That's great.
Okay, now let me ask you something about those days and changes.

Was there something that stands out in your mind as being, you know, other than the women being admitted into A&M, other things that might have had a great impact and changed the way things were done in that department or influenced its growth?
We didn't have a girl or ladies in industrial arts or vocational industrial program immediately.
But ultimately, as girls and women were permitted, we did begin to get students interested.
Did that surprise you?
No.
We welcomed it.
That was one of the great things that turned A&M around, the women coming here.
A lot of people fought it for the state, but it's the best thing that ever happened to A&M.
There was a tremendous growth, maybe it wasn't as noticeable then, but
Did the growth that came about so quickly have any influence on your interaction with students, on your ability to counsel with students and so forth?
No, we just had more students.
That complicated it.
Plus we had more students.
But students are all alike.
So you still had enough time, though, to work with them?
Yeah, we made time.
Because students was our business.
Do you have a feel... Boone is one of them.
Sir?
Boone is one of them.
Right.
A feel for how the perceptions of outsiders, what kind of perceptions did they have for this, you know, Department of Industrial Education?
How was it viewed across the state or even beyond that or within the university?
What were people's perceptions of the department you have?
Well, those interested in...
of occupational oriented programs were very pleased, especially in the industrial arts and vocational education areas when A&M got into the advanced degree programs.
We had a lot of people who wanted to come here that had gotten their undergraduate work other places to do their doctorate here.
There was none in the state in our field.
Was this the first one?
Yes, ma'am.
Did a lot of them come about as a result of that?
Are there a lot of people now that offer that degree?
Yes.
North Texas, East Texas.
I'm positive of those schools offering the advanced degree, doctoral degree.
But it was A&M then that offered the first one in the state.
The University of Texas offered a doctorate degree, but not in industrial education.
People who had industrial arts and vocational industrial backgrounds could go there, but they got no more of their field.
You tell me a little bit about some of the highlights, and you were here for 27 years.

Some of the things that maybe stand out in your mind is having had a lot of significance or maybe personal gratification of things that happened other than establishing this doctoral program, which I'm sure was probably one of your great contributions along with other things.
Well, we felt that the doctoral program being offered here in all fields was very beneficial to Texas A&M University.
And as a result, I think the
people throughout the state had a much higher regard for A&M because they were doing that.
In fact, we had to offer a doctorate degree for quite a few years before the normal state teachers colleges got into that.
Any insights or observations or maybe some little anecdotes or something that happened

that would not be in any documents that are just from your own personal experience, be someone or some individuals that might have either influenced you or you felt you had had influence on that went on to do.
I think a difference that we noticed immediately was when we started offering the advanced degrees was that we attracted
people from other states throughout the United States, which benefited our program as well as the university because they got a good impression of Texas A&M.
They used to think of it as an all-male Hick school.
And of course, we were glad to get additional exposure for our own department.
Because not many in the United States had doctoral programs in our field.
In fact, I think we were about the third.
Penn State and the University of Missouri, I think, were the only two that had doctoral programs in our field.
It took a long time to get people, general people, citizens, oriented to the idea that we were not shop people, per se.
But there were a lot of facets in the educational program that they could get in no way other than to go to get advanced degrees.
Do you have a feel for where that area is now, or how it has evolved?
What is going on in the schools now that relates to these beginnings?
I think because of the advanced degree,
And the status that it put, industrial education, vocational education, gave us a much higher recognition in the public schools by the administrators.
They used to think we were all wood butchers.
I think A&M led the pack.
in doing this thing, because I taught at East Texas before I came here.
And our idea at East Texas was A&M is a cow college.
When I got here, I saw little cows.
Okay.
Well, as the administrators began to change their view of these teachers, what did that do
to people wanting to come into education when it became, you know, a college of education and to go out there and be able to teach.
Are you thinking about our field?
Mm-hmm.
In industrial.
I think it gave our field a good recognition and an upgrading of the status of industrial education by everyone.
Now industrial education
that is offered in the schools for students?
Is it for students that just want to be able to get a skill to go out to work rather than continue with their education?
What is the thrust?
Well, first, I think it almost has to be pointed out, is the industrial education being offered in the public schools under the jurisdiction of federal Smith Hughes and what is it?
Barton Act?
Vocational acts.
National vocational acts.
Because if they graduate under that, the assumption is those teachers will train high school kids to go to industry.
That's not always true.
If they graduated from a program that was both

general educational as well as vocational, then the hope was that the youngsters in high school would have a better appreciation of industry and people that work in industry as they would in agriculture.
I haven't seen the funny papers yet.
You must get them.
That's all I ever read was the funny papers.
That's probably the best part.
It keeps me happy.
So then, how is that handled in the schools now?
Are they still very separate?
You know, the vocational programs still totally separate from the regular general education, do you know?
In the high schools?
Mm-hmm.
Well, observation of it is that if you have a teacher who is qualified for vocational certification, it means that the high school can get federal monies.
for the teacher.
And in turn, they would then expect those teachers to intensify entry in the industry when they get out of high school, or before they get out of high school.
Was there always very strong federal support for all these programs when you were involved in it?
A lot of federal funding and state funding as well?
Yeah, states had to match federal.
Is that still true?
I presume it is.
I haven't been in the racket so long.

You probably are familiar with a lot of the current reforms in education and what parole is trying to do and what a lot of people are saying about the vocational and these changes, for example, now the core curriculum coming in at A&M and everybody has to take all these particular courses.
What is your reaction to that, to those kinds of reforms?
We haven't seen enough of it yet to know how effective it is in the long run.
We have felt, going back a bit now, that those graduating in college in vocational type programs, industrial and vocational, have a better opportunity to get children in the secondary schools
acquainted with industry and other occupational areas because they can't all go to college.
And the trade and industrial and vocational homemaking and all of those, that is their purpose generally, to get high school kids ready to go to industry.
They don't care whether they go to college or not.
Or they don't, so I won't say that.
But if they don't go, they've got a good background.
Industrial arts is mostly sort of dual.
We want them to get some appreciation of vocations, but we also want them to get an idea of what industry is all about.
Do you feel like there is some kind of a thrust or movement to de-emphasize vocational or not
to not give it, because it was in its heyday, say, back in the, what, 60s or 70s?
And then it seemed like the pendulum has swung a little bit.
Is it likely to go back, or where do you feel that is right now?
Do you have a feel for that?
Well, I don't have a real feel for it, probably because I'm too deeply involved in it, always have been.
I think there's...
a feeling by some high school administrators that they want the kids to go to college.
And they don't want them to stop when they get out of high school.
Probably the more liberal thinking nowadays is that they need to have a choice.
And a good background in vocational and in industrial
To me, it's good for everybody.
Probably because I'm involved.
Well, it's fine.
I had one person tell me...
They can go overboard, too.
Somebody told me, though, that back in the old days, we're talking about the 50s probably, this particular person had chosen the vocational.
Then he changed his mind and wanted to go to college and was punished, was even thrown out of school.
you know, for wanting to go to college.

And he felt very strongly about what you're saying, that you should have a choice, but just because you choose when you maybe start going into high school that you want to go to the vocational route, if halfway down the road you decide maybe you would like to go to college, that you still should have that option.
Does it track students into something where then they can't get out?
I think the programs ought to be built so the teachers don't try to influence them.
Against the kids' will.
Now, parents may be of such financial status that they can't send their children to college.
But by the same token, they don't want them to be wood butchers.
I mean, there was.
I don't think it's much anymore, because the people that felt that are much older now.
Shut up.
The younger ones who are getting into that classification, I think, can understand that occupational orientation via information or experiences are good for everybody and do not curtail them.
In closing, is there anything that you would like to summarize your career in this field?
Obviously, you love it and you feel very strongly about it.
Is there something that you would like to close with that has influenced you or you have influenced?
I don't know.
I've influenced everybody, actually.
Ten years ago I would have said that we have to keep people from saying derogatory comments about occupational educational type programs.
On a college level or any level?
Anywhere.
Okay.
I think today it is a well accepted fact that it might have been a good idea for all
students to have had some experiences of that type because they are as valuable as other courses they take.
A lot of this, you know, has been generated through superintendents, pro and con.
Some of them think we all ought to have a lot of it.
Other superintendents say we're going to have no vocational programs.
We don't want our students influenced that way.
We want them to come up culturally.
You know, I've run into that.
Not anymore, but I have run into that.
When I go on, or more when I was at East Texas, I'd be invited to talk to various groups, the Waters Alliance, or the industrial educational oriented groups.
And it was kind of hard to
get them to understand that.
Now, people, I don't think, think begrudgingly against occupational type courses in public schools anymore.
How do you think that would affect the dropout?
You know, there's such a scary thing right now about dropouts and potential, you know, the at-risk student, that's all you're hearing about right now.
Do you feel that this could have an impact if it was emphasized more on keeping students in school, possibly?
Probably if they could earmark the kids that are going that way, that need to go that way.
I think probably one thing that has helped us more than anything is guidance counselors now.
We didn't used to have them.
In what way?
Just by being able to lead the students into?
Yeah, by not being narrow-minded, but having broad concepts of
Occupational opportunities.
I don't mean industry.
I mean all occupational opportunities.
Career education is what I'm trying to say.
It's called career education now.
I don't know if that's a more acceptable term or not.
It depends on who we are.
To me, it doesn't matter.
But some of you said, oh, I want my boy to go to vocational school.
No, I don't want him to go be a wood butcher or carpenter.
But if you can talk to them about careers, then that's something different.
That's right.
I run into that.
Well, Dr. Gronemann, I really appreciate your taking this time to visit with me.
It's been very enlightening, and I appreciate your time.
I appreciate what you did to get these things for A&M, because people like you have had so much influence on making A&M what it is today.
I've enjoyed my stay here.
It's gone fast.
Glad to have you.
Since 1940.
